docs.abstract: Why should the F.A.A. continue to permit a system prone to going haywire aboard an aircraft?
docs.snippet: Why should the F.A.A. continue to permit a system prone to going haywire aboard an aircraft?
docs.lead_paragraph: The struggle that the two Lion Air pilots waged with their out-of-control 737 Max 8 aircraft last October was both tenacious and terrifying. A new automated safety feature on the jet designed to prevent stalls instead kept sending the aircraft into a dive. Again and again, the pilots pulled the jet’s nose up, only to have a faulty sensor reverse their actions. For some reason, they couldn’t or didn’t cut off the automation, which ultimately sent the year-old Boeing jet into a steep dive and a crash that would claim 189 lives.

headline.main: Ground the Boeing Max 8. There Are Too Many Concerns.
